text.tspan: excessive enrolment in extra-curricular activities as a source of stress, three students also
mentioned stress due to a lack of participation in extra-curricular activities. The researcher
speculates that this may be due to the lack of outdoor sports or boredom due to inactivity while
being stuck at home. Students also experienced exhaustion due to continuous online classes and
increased eye strain due to prolonged screen time. They reported an inability to learn via online
classes due to a tiresome schedule, limited interaction between teachers and students, and
unsatisfactory rules for the virtual classroom. Students were held responsible for poor network
connectivity and removed from the class if their video was seen switched off. They expressed
concerns over the vast load of the syllabus to be covered in a shorter span of time. The inability
to grasp concepts due to limited interaction with teachers and network connectivity issues is seen
more vividly as a student wrote, "I'm not able to cope with the other students because I'm a slow
grabber. I need time to understand things, and just because of this, I lag behind, and this worries
me a lot" (Participant 217). Furthermore, some of the students were unable to contact the teacher
personally to discuss doubts and queries. On the other hand, a few students also observed
increased concentration in their studies; they expressed a better understanding because they
studied for a longer period than before the COVID-19 lockdown.
